<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,1458,1790]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,312,1686,1712]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Remarks</emphasis>
: The aedeagal shaft is very variable in this species with respect to its width in lateral view and the presence or absence of a spine on the ventral margin (compare 
<figureCitation box="[948,1129,1725,1751]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–10" captionStartId="45.[151,274,1621,1645]" captionTargetBox="[167,1414,198,1572]" captionTargetId="figure-59@45.[151,1436,173,1674]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="FIGURES 9–10. Deltocephalus species. 9, D. brunnescens Distant, o: head and thorax, lateral view; p: apex of aedeagus, q: aedeagus lateral view, r: subgenital plate, style, aedeagus and connective dorsal view; s: male genital segment, lateral view. 10, D. infirmus Melichar." pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Figs 9k and 9q</figureCitation>
). However, as both forms can occur in the same population (in this case the series from 
<collectingCountry box="[868,987,1764,1790]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
), they are regarded as a single species.
</paragraph>
